Also can I substitute maybe 50% strong whole meal flour?
Thanks</div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-921121" class="indented"><a id="comment-921121"></a><article class="comment comment__indented-wrapper comment__indented-wrapper-1"><div class=" comment__indented comment__indented-1"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-281803-1415360830.jpg?itok=HKYHujSC" width="40" height="40" alt="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" title="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">goodfoodteam</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 28th Apr, 2016</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">If you put a hole in the bagels after the first rise the hole is likely to close up again as the yeast continues to work in the dough. If you replace some of the flour with wholemeal you may need to add a drop more liquid when you first mix it as wholemeal flour is more absorbent than white because of the bran content in it. Let us know how you get on.</div></div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-767246"><a id="comment-767246"></a><article class="comment"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"> <span class="comment__author-picture--no-login"></span></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">AnnaWh</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 22nd May, 2014</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">My bagels deflated quite a lot is that because of over-proving or maybe not being gentle enough when adding to the water? Many thanks</div></div></div></div> </article></div></div><div><div id="comment-wrapper-769566" class="indented"><a id="comment-769566"></a><article class="comment comment__indented-wrapper comment__indented-wrapper-1"><div class=" comment__indented comment__indented-1"> <header class="comment__header"><div class="comment__author-picture"><div class="user-picture"> <img src="//www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/pictures/picture-281803-1415360830.jpg?itok=HKYHujSC" width="40" height="40" alt="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" title="goodfoodteam&#039;s picture" /></div></div><div class="comment__author-name"> <span class="username">goodfoodteam</span></div><div class="comment__date"> 2nd Jun, 2014</div> </header><div class="comment__text"><div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">Yes, it does sound like you may have over proved the bagels, be as gentle as you can as well when transfering them to the pan. Thanks.</div></div></div></div></div> </article></div></div></div></div></div><div id="fragment-tip" class="section-comments__single-tab-content"><div class="comment__no-comments-wrapper"><span class="comment__no-comments-title">Be the first to suggest a tip for this recipe...</span>Got your own twist on this recipe? Or do you have suggestions for possible swaps and additions? Weâ€™d love to hear your ideas.<div class="comment__no-comments-sign-in"><a href="/user/login?destination=recipes/edds-bagels">Sign in</a> or <a href="/user/register?destination=recipes/edds-bagels">create your My Good Food account</a> to join the discussion.</div></div></div></div> </section></div></div> <aside class="col span4"><div id="ad-mpu-premium-1-wide" class="ad-mpu-premium-1-wide"><div class="ad ad--mpu-premium-1-wide" id="ad-manager-ad-mpu_premium_1_wide-c304fa634f"><script type="text/javascript">Drupal.GPT.createSlot("ad-manager-ad-mpu_premium_1_wide-c304fa634f", function () {var m = Drupal.GPT.buildSizeMapping([[[0